Seventeen species of the genus
Dracocephalum (Lamiaceae)
are distributed in Mongolia , and many of them are known as medicinal plants (
; Ozek ¨et al., 2013;
,
).
D. fruticulosum Steph. ex Willd.
is called “Jivzipriyangu,” and its medicinal preparations are used in traditional Mongolian medicine for the treatment of liver disease, wounds, and blood clots (
).
D . nutans
L. is called “priyangku” in Tibetan medicine, and its medicinal preparations are used internally for abdominal and kidney inflammation (
). Essential oils are one of the features of various
Dracocephalum spp.
plants, and cis -chrysanthenol acetate and trans -verbenol from
D . fruticulosum
(Ozek ¨et al., 2013), as well as pinocamphone and β- pinene from
D . nutans
, were reported as chemical constituents of volatile oils (
;
).
D . foetidum Bunge
in C.F.von Ledebour is a medicinal plant used for the treatment of inflammation, and monoterpene glycosides, phenylpropanoid oligomers, and flavonoids were identified in this plant in a previous study (
).

Every year, approximately 600 million cases of foodborne diseases and 420,000 deaths occur worldwide (World Health Organization, 2021). Norovirus, which causes acute gastroenteritis, is the leading cause of nonbacterial foodborne diseases (

; 

). Norovirus is a nonenveloped RNA virus belonging to the family 

Caliciviridae

that was first identified in 1972 from an outbreak of acute gastroenteritis that occurred in 
1968 in
Norwalk, OH, 
USA
(

). Norovirus causes watery diarrhea, vomiting, nausea, mild fever, and severe illness and can be transmitted through person-to-person contact (

). Although people of all ages are infected with norovirus, children younger than 5 years old and persons over 65 years old are at the highest risk of norovirus infection, which is associated with hospitalizations and death (

). In addition, norovirus can cause long-term chronic gastroenteritis in immunocompromised patients (

). Norovirus also causes significant economic losses in the healthcare and food industries (

). Therefore, to minimize the burden to health and wealth, norovirus infection should be controlled. Although a method for human norovirus replication using stem cell-derived human intestinal enteroids, obtained from intestinal tissue biopsies, was reported in 2016 (

), easier methods using established cell lines have not yet been developed. Because of these limitations in basic research, no specific drugs and vaccines against norovirus have been developed. Thus, one of the best ways to control norovirus infection and minimize losses is the disinfection of viruses remaining in the environment.

However, alcohol-based disinfectants are not an efficient option for the inactivation of nonenveloped 

Caliciviridae

viruses (

). Since the tolerability to alcohol seems to be different among different norovirus strains (

), the use of high concentrations of chlorine bleach (sodium hypochlorite) is recommended for the disinfection of norovirus. However, chlorine has corrosive activity and irritates the skin, mucous membrane, and upper airways (

).

Hence, to find effective norovirus-inactivating materials with no adverse effects on human health, we focused on plant-derived components. We have previously reported (

) that components derived from the Mongolian herbal plant 

Saxifraga spinulosa

, including flavonoids and galloyl glycosides (

), showed virucidal activities against feline calicivirus (FCV), which is known as one of the surrogates of human norovirus, murine norovirus, influenza A virus, and SARS-CoV-2.

