The assignments of 1 H and 13 C NMR spectra of 1 (methanol- d 4 ) are shown in Table 1 . Two sets of o -coupling pattern protons in the aromatic field ( δH 7.42, 2H, br d, J = 8.5 Hz, H-2 ′ and H-6 ′ ; 6.95, 2H, br d, J = 8.5 Hz, H-3 ′ and H-5 ′ ; 6.22, 1H, d, J = 2.0 Hz, H-6; 6.18, 1H, d, J = 2.0 Hz, H-8) and an ABX coupling system protons ( δH 5.43, 1H, dd, J = 13.0, 3.0 Hz, H-2; 3.16, 1H, dd, J = 17.0, 13.0 Hz, H-3ax; 2.76, 1H, dd, J = 17.0, 3.0 Hz, H-3eq) suggested the presence of a flavanone skeleton. The pseudo-axial or equatorial orientation of H 2 -3 were determined by the large coupling constant ( J = 13.0 Hz) between H-2 and H-3ax (
). The methoxy proton δH 3.81 (3H, s) and carbon δC 55.8 resonances were observed, and the methyl proton was long-range coupled with the C-4 ′ ( δC 161.6), which showed that the aglycone moiety was isosakuranetin. In 13 C NMR spectra, six glucosidic carbons ( δC 101.2, 74.7, 77.9, 71.6, 75.6, 65.4, C-Glc-1–6) and two carbonyl carbons ( δC 170.3 and 168.8) were observed as a feature of this compound (
;
). The glucose proton [ δH 4.48 (1H, dd, J = 11.5, 2.5 Hz, H-Glc-6), 4.25 (1H, dd, J = 11.5, 7.5 Hz, H-Glc-6)] and carbon ( δC 65.4, C-Glc-6) resonances were lower field shifted than those of isosakuranetin 7- O -glucopyranoside ( 3 ), showing the presence of an acyl moiety at C-Glc-6 of 1 . The molecular formula of 1 was determined to be C 25 H 26 O 13 based on HRFABMS data (positive): m / z 535.1455 [M+H] + (calcd for C 25 H 27 O 13 : 535.1451). The molecular formula for an additional C 3 H 2 O 3 corresponded to a malonyl moiety compared with isosakuranetin 7- O -glucopyranoside ( 3 ) (C 22 H 24 O 10 ). In a heteronuclear multiple bond correlation (HMBC) spectrum ( Fig. 2 ), H-Glc-6 was long-range coupled with the malonyl carbon at δC 168.8. These 1 H and 13 C NMR chemical shifts of Glc-6 and HMBC correlation showed a malonyl group bond to C-Glc-6. In an electronic CD (ECD) spectrum ( Fig. 3 ), the negative Cotton effect at 286 nm showed the (2 S )-absolute configuration of 1 (
;
). HPLC sugar analysis after acid hydrolysis indicated that the sugar moiety was D-glucopyranose. The coupling constant of the anomeric proton ( J = 7.5 Hz) suggested its β- configuration. Therefore, 1 was determined to be (2 S )-isosakuranetin 7- O -β- D-(6 ′′ - O -malonyl)glucopyranoside, as shown in Fig. 1 .

The molecular formula of 19 was determined to be C 27 H 34 O 14 based on HRFABMS data (positive): m / z 583.2028 [M+H] + (calcd for C H O: 583.2027). In the 1 H NMR spectrum of 19 (DMSO‑ d , 27 35 14 6 Table 1 ), two sets of aromatic proton resonances ( δH 6.99, 2H, brd, J = 8.5 Hz, H-3 and H-5 and 7.09, 2H, brd, J = 6.5 Hz, H-2 and H-6) and ( δH 6.68, 1H, d, J = 7.5 Hz, H-10, 7.15, 1H, dd, J = 8.0, 7.5 Hz, H-11, and 6.72, 1H, d, J = 8.0 Hz, H-12) were observed, and the former and latter coupling system protons suggested the presence of a p -substituted benzene ring and trisubstituted benzene ring moieties, respectively. The aromatic carbons [ δC 135.1 (C-1), 128.8 (C-2 and C-6), 116.4 (C-3 and C-5), 155.6 (C-4), 141.0 (C-9), 120.1 (C-10), 130.6 (C-11), 113.9 (C-12), 156.8 (C-13), and 119.9 (C-14)] were assigned to the two benzene rings by heteronuclear multiple quantum coherence (HMQC) and HMBC correlations ( Fig. 4 ). In the aliphatic field of the 1 H NMR spectrum, two methylene protons at δH 2.75 (2H, m, H-7) and 2.88 (2H, m, H-8) were observed and their coupling with each other was confirmed by the 1 H– 1 H COSY spectrum of 19 . This result suggested the presence of an – CH 2 - CH 2 - moiety. In the HMBC spectrum of 19 , H-7 was long-range coupled with C-2 and C-6, and H-8 was coupled with C-10 and C-14, showing a dihydrostylbene skeleton. The carbonyl carbon at δC 170.5 (C-15) had no HMBC correlation, and it was hypothesized that the carbonyl group was bonded to C-14 compared to lunularic acid (
). The HMBC correlations from H-11 to C-9 and the oxygenated carbon (C-13) and H-10 and H-12 to C-14 supported this conclusion. These data showed that 19 had a 4- O -13-hydroxy-14-carboxydihydrostylbene moiety as its aglycone ( Fig. 4 ). In the 13 C NMR spectrum of 19 , 12 oxygenated carbon resonances were observed at δC 99.3, 82.8, 76.1, 69.4, 76.9, 60.6 (C-Glc-1 – 6) and δC 104.6, 74.8, 75.9, 69.6, 76.8, 60.6 (C-Glc-II-1 – 6), and these data showed the presence of two glycosyl moieties (
;
). HPLC sugar analysis of 19 after acid hydrolysis suggested that the sugar units were D-glucopyranose. The coupling constants of the anomeric protons of H-Glc-1 ( J = 7.0 Hz) and H-Glc-II-1 ( J = 8.0 Hz) showed β- configurations. In the HMBC spectrum, the H-Glc-II-1 proton resonance at δH 4.48 (1H, d, J = 8.0 Hz) was long-range coupled with C-Glc-2, and H-Glc-1 at δH 4.91 (1H, d, J = 7.0 Hz) was coupled with C-4. Therefore, 19 was determined to be 2-hydroxy-6-{2-[4- O -β- D-glucopyranosyl(1 → 2)- O -β- D-glucopyranosylphenyl] ethyl}benzoic acid, as shown in Fig. 1 .

The HRFABMS data (positive) of 21 ( m / z 822.3188 [M+H] + , calcd for C 39 H 51 NO 18 : 822.3185) showed that the molecular formula of 21 was C 39 H 50 NO 18 . In the 1 H NMR spectrum of 21 , three sets of aromatic proton resonances ( δH 7.03, 2H, d, J = 8.5 Hz, H-3 and H-5 and 7.19, 2H, d, J = 8.5 Hz, H-2 and H-6), ( δH 7.53, 2H, overlapping, H-2 ′ and H-6 ′ , 7.37, 3H, overlapping, H-3 ′ , H-4 ′ , and H-5 ′ ), and ( δH 7.51, 1H, d, J = 16.0 Hz, H-7 ′ and 6.56, 1H, d, J = 16.0 Hz, H-8 ′ ) were observed. The carbonyl carbon at δC 168.7 (C-9 ′ ) and the HMBC correlation from H-8 ′ to C-1 ′ ( δC 136.4) showed the presence of a cinnamoyl moiety ( Fig. 4 ). The coupling constant between H-7 ′ and H-8 ′ ( J = 16.0 Hz) showed their E -configuration. In the aliphatic field of 1 H NMR, proton resonances of – CH 2 - CH 2 - moiety ( δH 2.82, 2H, brt, J = 7.0 Hz, H-7 and 3.52, 2H, overlapping, H-8) were observed, and H-7 was long-range coupled with C-1, C-2, and C-6. These data suggested the presence of a p -substituted phenylethyl moiety. The presence of one nitrogen was indicated by HRFABMS. The chemical shift value of C-8 ( δC 42.4) suggested that C-8 bonded to a nitrogen. The H-8 proton was long-range coupled with the C-9 ′ carbonyl carbon of amide. These data showed that the aglycone of 21 was (2 E )- N -[2-(4-hydroxyphenyl)ethyl]-3-phenyl-2-propenamide. The three anomeric proton resonances ( δH 5.73, 1H, d, J = 1.5 Hz, H-Rha-1; 4.61, 1H, d, J = 7.5 Hz, H-Glc-I-1; 4.43, 1H, d, J = 8.0 Hz, H-Glc-II-1) were observed in the 1 H NMR spectrum of 21 . The homonuclear Hartmann–Hahn (HOHAHA) spectra showed spin system protons from each anomeric proton, as discussed below. Their corresponding carbons were assigned by HMQC spectrum of 21 . These suggested the presence of one rhamnosyl and two glucosyl moieties (
;
). The peaks of L-rhamnopyranose and D-glucopyranose derivatives were confirmed by HPLC sugar analysis after acid hydrolysis. The α- and β- orientations of L-rhamnopyranosyl and D-glucopyranosyls were determined by their coupling constants J = 1.5 Hz and 7.5–8.0 Hz, respectively. The HMBC correlations from H-Rhm-2 ( δH 4.35, 1H, dd, J = 3.0, 1.5 Hz) to C-Glc-I-1 ( δC 105.9), H-Glc-I-1 to C-Rha-2 ( δC 79.9), H-Rhm-3 ( δH 4.16, 1H, dd, J = 10.0, 3.0 Hz) to C-Glc-II-1 ( δC 106.6), and H-Glc-II-1 to C-Rha-3 ( δC 79.6) showed that the sugar chain was O -β- D-glucopyranosyl-(1 → 2)-[ O -β- D-glucopyranoside-(1 → 3)]- O -α- L-rhamnopyranosyl. In addition, there were two acetyl groups in 21 ( δH 2.00, 3H, s; 2.09, 3H, s; δC 172.7; 21.1). The lower field shifted oxymethylene resonances ( δH 4.36, 1H, dd, J = 12.0, 2.0 Hz and 4.31, 1H, dd, J = 12.0, 6.5 Hz) were assigned to H-Glc-II-6 protons by the below procedure. In the HOHAHA spectra, when H-Glc-II-1 ( δH 4.43) was irradiated, the correlation with H-Glc-II-5 ( δH 3.51) was shown. Moreover, the H-Glc-II-5 proton correlated with the H-Glc-II-6 protons in the 1 H– 1 H COSY spectrum. In the HMBC spectrum, H-Rha-4 ( δH 5.11, 1H, t, J = 10.0 Hz) and H-Glc-II-6 ( δH 4.31, 1H, dd, J = 12.0, 6.5 Hz) were long-range coupled with the carbonyl carbons of the acetyl groups. The lower shifted carbon resonances ( δC 73.7, C-Rha-4; 64.9, C-Glc-II-6) supported this conclusion. Based on these data, 21 was determined to be (2 E )- N -{2-[4- O -β- D-glucopyranosyl-(1 → 2)-[ O -β- D-(6- O -acetyl)glucopyranosyl-(1 → 3)]- O -α- L-(4- O -acetyl)rhamnopyranosyl]ethyl}-3-phe nyl-2-propenamide.

In addition to the above isolated compounds, for discussion of the structure–activity relationship, previously isolated compounds (

), including a phenylpropanoid trimer (
22
