Some early research showed that naturally occurring dietary flavonoids possessed antiviral activities against several human viruses (
). In addition, many studies have shown multiple antiviral mechanisms of flavonoids, such as virucidal action against extracellular virions, blocking of virus entry into a cell, and inhibition of viral enzymatic activities essential for viral replication (
;
). In our study, a total of 21 flavonoids derived from
D. fruticulosum
,
D . nutans
, and
D . foetidum
were tested for FCV-inactivating activity, and only 5 of them ( 1–3 , 5 , and 7 ) showed antiviral activities. In particular, 1 and 2 may have more potent virucidal activities than those of other flavonoids because these two compounds showed virucidal activity after 6 h of incubation. Thus, flavanones ( 1–3 and 5 ) were more effective against FCV than flavones ( 6–14 and 27–33 ), and flavanone glucosides ( 1–3 and 5 ) showed higher activities than that of naringenin ( 4 ). Although 0.5 mM naringenin ( 4 ) did not show any virucidal activities against FCV and murine norovirus after 2 h of incubation (
), antiviral activities of naringenin ( 4 ) were reported against dengue virus (FrabasileKoishi et al., 2017; Zandi et al.,), zika virus (
), and hepatitis C virus (
). As the isolated 4 ′ - O -methyl naringenin (isosakuranetin) glycosides ( 1 and 2 ) showed higher activities than that of naringenin ( 4 ), they may have the potential to be used as virucidal compounds.

In addition, we found five rosmarinic acid-related virucidal compounds, namely, 15–17 , 22 , and 25 . Rosmarinic acid ( 15 ) is known to have antiviral, anti-inflammatory, antibacterial, and antioxidant activities (
;
). Compounds 16 , 17 , and 22 are typical rosmarinic acid derivatives. Interestingly, 25 is a rosmarinic acid glucoside. As the acylated rosmarinic acid glucosides ( 23 and 24 ) and the Z -rosmarinic acid glucoside ( 26 ) did not show activity, the effect of the glucosyl moiety remains uncertain. Phenylpropanoid oligomers have been isolated from various plants of the family Lamiaceae (
,
). In addition to the virucidal activity of rosmarinic acid, antiviral activities have been reported for caffeic acid derivatives. For example, some caffeic acid oligomers from
Mesona chinensis
showed antiviral activities against the respiratory syncytial virus (
). Rosmarinic acid and its derivatives are known to have tannin-like activity (
), and the results of this study revealed potentially broader antiviral activity spectra of phenylpropanoid oligomers.

Crandell–Rees feline kidney (CRFK) cells and FCV (F9 strain) were provided by Dr. K. Maeda ( Yamaguchi University, Yamaguchi , Japan ). CRFK cells were not tested for mycoplasma infection. They were cultured in the viral growth medium after FCV inoculation, as previously described (
). After 3 days of incubation, the supernatant of the cell culture medium containing FCV was collected and used for the FCV suspension. The viral titers of the FCV suspensions were 3.25–5.75 log 10 TCID 50 /ml. The
Dracocephalum spp.
-derived compounds at a concentration of 25 μg/ml or DMSO, used as the solvent control, were added to the FCV suspensions. All FCV suspensions were incubated at 25 ◦ C for 6 and 48 h. After incubation, these suspensions were inoculated into CRFK cells, and 10-fold serial dilutions were performed in the cell culture medium. Three days later, their cytopathic effects on FCV-infected cells were observed, and the viral titers (log 10 TCID 50 /ml) were calculated using the Behrens–Karber ¨method (Karber ¨, 1931). The differences in the titers of FCV suspensions in each test group vs. the DMSO group were evaluated as previously described (
).
